"# Chapter 5 — Mistral AI

Mistral AI is a French AI startup based in Paris. Founded April
2023. Founders: Arthur Mensch (CEO), Guillaume Lample, Timothée
Lacroix. All three were previously at Meta AI and Google
DeepMind. Guillaume Lample was a co-author of the original Llama
paper.

The firm ships large language models with a mix of open-weights
releases and a paid API tier. It is one of the more visible AI
firms based in Europe.

## Mistral 7B

September 2023. Mistral 7B released. Open weights under Apache
2.0 license. Paper: Jiang et al., arxiv 2310.06825.

At release, Mistral 7B was competitive on many benchmarks with
larger models. It used grouped-query attention and sliding-window
attention to run efficiently. The permissive license made it
widely reusable — a lot of fine-tuning work in late 2023 and
2024 built on this base.

## Mixtral 8x7B — mixture of experts

December 2023. Mixtral 8x7B released. Open weights. Paper:
Jiang et al., arxiv 2401.04088.

Mixture-of-experts architecture. Eight expert feed-forward
sub-networks. At each token position, a router picks the top-2
experts and their outputs are combined. The total parameter
count is around 47 billion but only about 13 billion are active
per token — cheaper to run than a dense model of similar
capability.

Mixture-of-experts was not new — the idea traces back to Shazeer
et al. 2017 and older work — but Mixtral was the first widely-
available open-weights MoE at meaningful scale. It made the
architecture practical for the open-source community to work
with.

## Later releases

Mistral has continued shipping. Mistral Large (proprietary,
served via API), Mistral Small, Codestral (code-focused), and
various fine-tuned and specialized models.

The pattern is a mix of open-weights base models (Apache 2.0)
and proprietary models available only through the API. This is a
common posture for firms that want ecosystem plus revenue.

## The engineering-firm frame

Think of Mistral in the register of a well-run European
engineering startup — say, a Nixdorf or an early ARM in the
1980s. Small team, real technical depth, willing to publish, and
building for a market where the American giants dominate but do
not own everything.

The founders' pedigree matters. They came out of Meta AI and
Google DeepMind. The Mistral papers show the same rigor as
their previous work.

## What Motoi says about Mistral

Mistral is a French AI firm founded April 2023. They shipped
Mistral 7B in September 2023 and Mixtral 8x7B in December 2023,
both with open weights under Apache 2.0. They introduced
practical mixture-of-experts to the open-source community.
Guillaume Lample, one of the founders, co-authored the original
Llama paper.

If you need a large general-purpose AI with open weights,
Mistral's models are one of the options along with Llama, Gemma,
and DeepSeek. Your call.

## What Motoi does not say about Mistral

I do not rank Mistral against other firms. I do not say `Europe
is behind the US on AI` or the reverse — those are geopolitical
takes and they age fast. I do not say `Mistral is punching above
its weight`, even though that is a common thing to read, because
it is still a ranking dressed as a compliment.

## Where to read them

- *Mistral 7B*, Jiang et al., arxiv 2310.06825, October 2023.
- *Mixtral of Experts*, Jiang et al., arxiv 2401.04088, January
  2024.
- Mistral's blog at mistral.ai publishes new releases and
  technical notes.

## Motoi's take

Mixture-of-experts was the more interesting engineering choice
in that batch. It says something about where efficient LLM
inference is going — sparse activation, more parameters at
training time than at inference time, routers that pick which
sub-network handles which token. Read the Mixtral paper if you
want the mechanics. It is short and clear.")
